\end{align*}

Similarly, we do the same thing but change the lower limit to √ℏ/(mω₀) instead of −√ℏ/(mω₀):
\begin{align*}
J=&amp;\hspace{15mm}|I|\\
&amp;=|(\alpha/\pi)^{1/4}[e^{-\alpha c^2}+e^{-\alpha d^2}]/({\sqrt{\alpha }})|\\
&amp;=|(\alpha/\pi)^{1/4}[e^{-\alpha d^2}+e^{-\alpha c^2}]/({\sqrt{\alpha }})|
\end{align*}
where c=√ℏ/(mω₀).
Again taking limits as c→√ℏ/(mω₀) and d→∞:

\begin{align*}
 J =&amp;\hspace{25mm} \lim_{c,d\rightarrow \infty} [( \alpha/\pi)^{1/4} ] [e^{-\alpha d^2}+e^{-\alpha c^2}]/({\sqrt{\alpha }})\\[6pt]&=(\alpha/\pi)^{1/4}e^{-1/2}
\end{align*}

Therefore, combining results for I and J together we get:

\begin{align*}
P(&amp;\text{outside})=|I|^2+|J|^2\\
&amp;=((\alpha/\pi)^{1/4}e^{-1/2})^2+(\alpha/\pi)^{1/4}e^{-1/2})^2\\
